No modification of the sound file was made. The recording was done with an iphone 4s in a residential area of the city with many trees. There is background noise from cars.
The sound is very similar to a submarine sonar. It starts at nightfall and continues pretty much until morning. There are breaks of 10-15 min sometimes, but it can usually go on for hours. It begun a few nights back and no one I asked has any recollection of hearing something similar, ever.
It comes from high up in the trees but it's at least 50m away from where the recording was taken.

rmk: First time was on July 1st and only after twilight, but it lasted all night. Same today, on the 2nd. They start when it's getting dark and take breaks sometimes. It sounds like it's coming from the rooftop of some four story buildings, but there are trees in between, so it might come from there as well. There's at least four different scattered locations from which the sound is coming from in this area. It sounds juvenile, but it could be a mating call too. They answer to the calls. This is all we know. Thank you!

The song I recorded was sung by a small gray bird (something like a blue tit in size, only with much duller plumage). The bird has a funny way of moving from tree to tree. It sings almost all day long. It prefers to hide, so it's really difficult to see. When I first recorded it, it was singing high in an oak tree. After it spotted me, it flew into a nearby bush and continued to sing. It seems to have different singing places, which is visits according to a certain routine. It also seems to have favorite spots.
The weather was fair (sunny), and the temperature was 25C.
